## Stage 1: Core Concepts (Week 1)

### The building blocks
| Concept | What it is |
|---|---|
| **Cluster** | A set of machines (nodes) running Kubernetes |
| **Node** | A single machine (VM or bare metal) in the cluster — has a `kubelet` agent |
| **Pod** | The smallest deployable unit — one or more containers that share network/storage |
| **Deployment** | Manages a set of identical Pods, handles rolling updates & self-healing |
| **Service** | Stable network endpoint that load-balances traffic to a set of Pods |
| **Namespace** | A virtual cluster-within-a-cluster for organizing resources |
| **ConfigMap / Secret** | Externalized configuration and sensitive data |
| **Volume / PersistentVolume** | Storage that outlives a Pod's lifecycle |

**Key insight:** you almost never create a Pod directly. You create a **Deployment**, which
creates and manages Pods for you (restarting them if they die, replacing them on updates).

### Install a local cluster to practice on
- **minikube** (single-node local cluster, most common for learning)
- **kind** (Kubernetes-in-Docker, lightweight, good for CI)
- Docker Desktop also has a built-in Kubernetes toggle

```bash
minikube start
kubectl cluster-info
kubectl get nodes
```

