## Stage 2: kubectl Basics (Week 1-2)

`kubectl` is the CLI you'll live in — think of it as `docker` but for a whole cluster.

```bash
kubectl get pods                      # list pods in current namespace
kubectl get pods -A                   # list pods in ALL namespaces
kubectl get pods -o wide              # more detail (node, IP)
kubectl get deployments
kubectl get services
kubectl get all                       # everything in current namespace
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>       # detailed info + events (great for debugging)
kubectl logs <pod-name>               # view logs
kubectl logs -f <pod-name>            # follow logs
kubectl logs <pod-name> -c <container>  # logs from a specific container (multi-container pod)
kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- bash   # shell into a pod
kubectl delete pod <pod-name>         # delete a pod (Deployment will recreate it!)
kubectl apply -f file.yaml            # create/update resources from a YAML file
kubectl delete -f file.yaml           # delete resources defined in a YAML file
kubectl explain pod                   # built-in docs for any resource type/field
```

**Project:** Run a simple nginx pod imperatively, then kill it and watch a Deployment
recreate it automatically.
```bash
kubectl create deployment mynginx --image=nginx --replicas=3
kubectl get pods
kubectl delete pod <one-of-the-pod-names>
kubectl get pods   # a new one appears automatically
```

