## Stage 3: Writing YAML Manifests (Week 2-3)

This is where you'll spend most of your time. Kubernetes is fundamentally YAML-driven.

### Pod (rarely written directly, but foundational)
```yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: my-app
  labels:
    app: my-app
spec:
  containers:
    - name: my-app
      image: my-app:1.0
      ports:
        - containerPort: 8080
```

### Deployment (what you'll actually use)
```yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: my-app
spec:
  replicas: 3
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: my-app
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: my-app
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: my-app
          image: my-app:1.0
          ports:
            - containerPort: 8080
          resources:
            requests:
              cpu: "250m"
              memory: "256Mi"
            limits:
              cpu: "500m"
              memory: "512Mi"
          livenessProbe:
            httpGet:
              path: /actuator/health
              port: 8080
            initialDelaySeconds: 20
            periodSeconds: 10
          readinessProbe:
            httpGet:
              path: /actuator/health
              port: 8080
            initialDelaySeconds: 5
```

### Service (stable network access to your Pods)
```yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: my-app-service
spec:
  selector:
    app: my-app          # matches the Deployment's Pod labels
  ports:
    - port: 80             # port the Service exposes
      targetPort: 8080      # port the container listens on
  type: ClusterIP           # default — internal only
```

**Service types:**
| Type | Use case |
|---|---|
| `ClusterIP` | Default. Internal-only, other Pods reach it via DNS name |
| `NodePort` | Exposes on a static port on every node (`<NodeIP>:<port>`) — dev/testing |
| `LoadBalancer` | Provisions a cloud load balancer (AWS/GCP/Azure) — production external access |
| `ExternalName` | Maps the Service to an external DNS name |

```bash
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
kubectl apply -f service.yaml
kubectl get svc                # see assigned ClusterIP / ports
kubectl port-forward svc/my-app-service 8080:80   # access locally without exposing publicly
```

**Project:** Take your Spring Boot Docker image, write a Deployment + Service YAML for it,
deploy to minikube, and access it via `kubectl port-forward` or `minikube service`.

