## Stage 10: Helm — Package Manager for Kubernetes (Week 7-8)

Writing raw YAML for every environment gets repetitive fast. **Helm** templates your
manifests so you can parameterize by environment (dev vs prod replica counts, image tags, etc.).

```bash
helm create mychart              # scaffold a new chart
helm install my-release ./mychart
helm upgrade my-release ./mychart
helm rollback my-release 1
helm uninstall my-release
helm list
helm repo add bitnami https://charts.bitnami.com/bitnami   # install pre-made charts
helm install my-postgres bitnami/postgresql
```

**Project:** Convert your Spring Boot Deployment + Service + ConfigMap into a Helm chart
with a `values.yaml` controlling replica count, image tag, and env vars per environment.

---

## Stage 11: Observability (Week 8+)

```bash
kubectl top nodes                 # resource usage per node (needs metrics-server)
kubectl top pods                  # resource usage per pod
kubectl get events --sort-by=.lastTimestamp   # cluster-wide recent events
```

- **Prometheus** — metrics collection
- **Grafana** — dashboards on top of Prometheus
- **Liveness vs Readiness probes** — liveness restarts unhealthy containers; readiness
  controls whether a Pod receives traffic (useful during slow startup)

---

## Stage 12 (Hero): CI/CD & GitOps (Week 9+)

- Build image → push to registry → update image tag → `kubectl apply` or Helm upgrade, all via CI (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, Jenkins)
- **GitOps** tools (ArgoCD, Flux) watch a Git repo and auto-sync the cluster to match — the manifests in Git are the single source of truth
- **kustomize** — patch-based YAML customization without templating (built into `kubectl apply -k`)

